<h1 style="font-size:2em;font-weight:800;margin-bottom:12px;">Why Does He Take Hours to Text Back?</h1>
<p style="color:#888;font-size:0.9em;margin-bottom:32px;">The real answer — not just the one that makes you feel better.</p>

<p>You sent the text. You watched it deliver. Two hours later — nothing.</p>
<p>So you check. Put the phone down. Check again. You tell yourself you're not checking. You check one more time.</p>

<h2 style="font-size:1.4em;margin-top:36px;">5 actual reasons he hasn't replied</h2>
<p><strong>1. He's genuinely not on his phone.</strong> Men check their phones less than women on average. He might be in a meeting, at the gym, or just not in texting mode.</p>
<p><strong>2. His response anxiety is lower than yours.</strong> If you have anxious attachment, you feel slow responses as a threat. He probably doesn't register time the same way.</p>
<p><strong>3. He doesn't know it matters to you.</strong> Unless you've told him, he has no idea a two-hour gap is causing you distress.</p>
<p><strong>4. He's thinking about what to say.</strong> Some people — especially more avoidant types — sit with a message before responding. They're not ignoring you.</p>
<p><strong>5. He is pulling back.</strong> Yes, sometimes. But this is one of five reasons, not the first one — even though your anxiety always goes there first.</p>

<h2 style="font-size:1.4em;margin-top:36px;">What NOT to send while you wait</h2>
<ul>
<li>A follow-up "did you get this?" — he got it</li>
<li>A casual "lol anyway" to seem unbothered — it doesn't work</li>
<li>That message you've been rewriting for 45 minutes — don't</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="font-size:1.4em;margin-top:36px;">What actually helps</h2>
<p>Put your phone in a different room. Set a 30-minute rule. Do literally anything else.</p>
